How do those who struggle make ends meet? To the average person, itâs presumed that assistance is sought through government social programs or initiatives from philanthropy and nonprofits. However, mutual aid, though overlapping in its goal to assist, differs from the above in its mode of operation, and despite many mutual aid networks cropping up during the height of the pandemic, is seldom brought up as a viable alternative to conventional avenues of assistance.

In the context of organizational theory, mutual aid is material redistribution that operates within our system, but is removed from the laws of economic individualism; in its simplest application, it exists as a communal transaction, where one party meets the needs of the other with little prerequisite. This vague definition gives rise to a broad structure â mutual aid is not limited in how it can be organized, and can operate on the larger scale, like GoFundMeâs crowdsourcing model, or as community initiatives like that of Asian Mutual Aid Group Inc., which is localized to New York Cityâs Chinese and Chinese-adjacent diaspora. Mutual aid also exists on the peer-to-peer scale and is not limited to the physical realm, as is the case of mutual aid groups found online (namely on Facebook).

For this analysis, data was sourced using posts on an active mutual aid Facebook group. We analyzed a sample size of 972 requests, extracting the amount asked, funded, and performed classification to categorize the request.

A quick browse paints a clear picture of what poverty looks like on a day-to-day basis. Members ask for anything from diapers, utilities, gas, groceries, household items, and housing, to manicures, game add-ons, concert tickets, and vacations. Requests can be both wants and needs of any amount, though you are more likely to receive funding if youâre asking for a smaller amount of something you need.

People come across the group in their search for resources online, and often are also receiving social assistance of some form, as shared anecdotally on posts. But as one member aptly put it: itâs never enough.

How did we get here? âOur society has become very siloed relative to how communities functioned 100 years ago,â said Laurie Styron, the CEO and Executive Director of the nonprofit watchdog, CharityWatch. âMany of our social interactions occur among strangers online rather than among neighbors, schoolmates, or via a religious affiliation like church or temple.â

There is also the issue of red-tape. In order to qualify for food or housing benefits like SNAP or the Housing Assistance Program, applicants need to meet certain income or demographic requirements while being left with the burden of proof that you actually need these services. Because recipients need to fall within an income bracket, there is often incentive to make less than the cut-off points in order to maintain eligibility for these programs, further perpetuating a cycle of poverty.

A summary from the Philanthropy Chronicle indicates charitable giving increased 4.7% in the first three quarters of 2022 but individual donors decreased 7.1% within the same timeframe. The nature of how charities get funded is a reflection of the shifting socioeconomic strata, explained Laurie. âIn the past a large volume of individuals donated small amounts of money to many different charities and causes,â she said.

âThese days, a small handful of extremely wealthy people are picking their pet causes and charities and directing large donations to a relatively small pool of organizations.â The end result, Laurie noted, âis that any charity not in that pool is going to struggle for funding as the pool of individual donors continues to shrink. And a lot of people who need help are going to slip through the cracks because [charities that can help them] donât happen to be the pet cause of a very wealthy donor or foundation.â
